Let $V_{0}$ be the volume of the universe and $R_{0}$ its radius nowadays. The numerical density of magnetic monopoles today can be calculated by $n_{M}\left(t_{0}\right)=p_{0} / V_{0}=3 p_{0} /\left(4 \pi R_{0}^{3}\right)$, where $p_{0}$ is the probability of existing a monopole in the current universe. Besides that, we can relate $n_{M}\left(t_{0}\right)$ with $n_{M}\left(t_{G U T}\right)$ by $n_{M}\left(t_{0}\right)=n_{M}\left(t_{G U T}\right) \cdot f_{0}^{-3} \cdot f_{N}^{-3}$, where $f_{0}$ is how much the universe expanded between the end of inflation and today, and $f_{N}$ is how much it expanded during the inflationary period. Making the equality between these two relations, we have:

$$
\begin{gathered}
n_{M}\left(t_{0}\right)=n_{M}\left(t_{G U T}\right) \cdot f_{0}^{-3} \cdot f_{N}^{-3}=\frac{3 p_{0}}{4 \pi R_{0}^{3}} \Rightarrow f_{N}=n_{M}\left(t_{G U T}\right) f_{0}^{-3} \frac{4 \pi R_{0}^{3}}{3 p_{0}} \\
