\end{gathered}
$$

The luminosity $L$ of a star in terms of its radius $R$ and temperature $T$ can be written using Stefan-Boltzmann's Law:

$$
L=4 \pi R^{2} \sigma T^{4}
$$

$\frac{L}{\left(R^{2} T^{4}\right)}$ is constant, and we know that the luminosity and radius of Recentus are $L_{R}=4 L_{\odot}$ and $R_{R}=4 R_{\odot}$ :

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{L_{R}}{\left(R_{R}^{2} T_{R}^{4}\right)} & =\frac{L_{\odot}}{\left(R_{\odot}^{2} T_{\odot}^{4}\right)} \\
T_{R} & =\frac{T_{\odot}}{\sqrt{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Using Wein's law, the peak emission wavelength of this star is $\lambda_{R}=\lambda_{\odot} \sqrt{2} \approx 710 \mathrm{~nm}$ and the corresponding peak emission frequency is $4.2 \times 10^{14} \mathrm{~Hz}$. Note that $\lambda_{\odot}=502 \mathrm{~nm}$ can be calculated from Wein's constant and $T_{\odot}$ which are in the TOC.

